name: Georgian Style Lover's Eye Portrait Jewellery - OMARINA Heirloom Collection Large Brooch Pin
description:
45mm x 35mm

The OMARINA Lover's Eye Brooch. Our lucky in love talisman.

History:  "Lover’s eyes" are one of the most captivating pieces of jewellery from the Georgian period. Believed to have begun with the Prince of Wales in the late 18th century and his secret lover, Mrs. Fitzherbert who exchanged eye miniature portraits rather than full miniatures so they both would have “anonymous” love tokens to cherish. (The bearers being the only one who could identify the sitter!)
This charming custom took hold and the aristocracy and wealthy soon began exchanging these tokens of love and affection. The fashion lasted from late 1790 until around 1825. Most take the form of brooches - like this one. They are often of women’s eyes which leads one to believe that ultimately they may have been given as tokens of affection for sisters and friends, as these brooches were not commonly worn by men. In fact, very few male eyes are found at all!

Image trapped inside thick domed glass in the Georgian 'miniature lover's eye portrait' style.

Brooch frame and clasp are both in matching 'antique bronze' finish metal.

Hand made by us, here in the OMARINA studio. Your brooch will arrive in a beautiful black gift box with black flocked velvet interior.

Currently FREE UK mainland economy postage!

(If you're in Glasgow and would like to collect in person, just email us immediately after checkout to arrange.)

Images by OMARINA. Shot on location at Lochranza Castle on the Isle of Arran, Scotland.

THE BIRDS 100% SILK Designer OMARINA SCARF Digital Art Print (Luxury Cravat Echarpe Foulard Sciarpa)
description:
Designer mens/womens 100% silk satin scarf by OMARINA.  

Beautifully drapey and lustrous unisex silk cravat style scarf, designed and hand made collaboratively by Scottish based fashion designer Marina Maclean and award winning British artist Omar Zingaro Bhatia. 

It features Omar's acclaimed artwork "The Birds" (native birds of Scotland) and has been digitally printed on both sides!. As you can see from the pictures, the detail and colour of each bird really 'pops' against the dark background. Fine black fringing elegantly finishes both ends. 

Length (including fringing) 180cm. Width 16cm.

Our silk scarves are sent Recorded Delivery and usually arrive the next working day.

Hand made in Scotland.
